    <p>
      I have not always been a developer. In fact, I started off my academic and professional journey believing the only way to satisfy my insatiable curiosity and independence was to start my own impactful business. I found the highest rated school for entrepreneurship in the country, Babson College, and spent the next four years learning about turning ideas into sustainable businesses. When I graduated, I joined a start up non-profit as the Marketing Director and Donor Manager. It wasn't right for me. I was bogged down in administrative decision-making when what I really wanted to do was build cool things. I took six months to travel around the U.S. and expose myself to as many new people as possible in hopes that I would find a discipline that would let me do that.
    </p>
    <p>
